Name: acceleration
Example question: A cheetah can run from rest to 26 m/s in 3 seconds. How much acceleration gains by cheetah?

Name: angular acceleration
Example question: A flywheel attains angular speed of 18.4 rad s^-1 from rest state in 2.3 sec. What is the magnitude of an angular acceleration gain by a flywheel?

Name: angular frequency
Example question: A simple harmonic oscillator has frequency 1/2 sec^-1. What is the angular frequency of a simple harmonic oscillator?

Name: angular momentum
Example question: A point mass of 0.250 kg is in horizontal uniform circular motion. The magnitude of its tangential velocity is 2 m s^-1. The point mass is located at the distance of 0.1 m from the center. What is magnitude of the angular momentum of a point mass?

Name: angular velocity
Example question: A point is located at the Earth's equator. Earth completes a full revolution (2 pi rad) in about 24 hours (86400 sec). What is the magnitude of angular velocity of point?

Name: center of mass
Example question: Two masses of 5 kg and 1 kg are located at distance of 6 m from each other. Find the centre of mass of the system. Assume heavier mass is located at the origin and the line joining two masses as the X-axis.

Name: centripetal acceleration
Example question: A child of mass 20 kg is sitting on the edge of a merry-go-round that has radius 3 m. The child revolving with uniform tangential velocity of magnitude 5 m s^-1. What is the magnitude of centriptal acceleration of the child?

Name: centripetal force
Example question: How much the centripetal force exerted on a 15000 kg jet plane that negotiates a 4000 m radius horizontal circular loop at 120 m s^-1?

Name: circumference
Example question: If the circumference of the circle is 16.33 m and the diameter is 5.2 m. What is the approximate value of pi?

Name: conservation of energy
Example question: A marble of 5 kg drops from the height of 10 m from the ground, where magnitude of the acceleration due to gravity is 9.8 m s^-2. What is the magnitude of the velocity of the marble just before hitting the ground?

Name: conservation of momentum
Example question: Two masses of 0.6 kg and 0.2 kg respectively are approaching each other with velocity of 3 m s^-1 along horizontal and frictionless surface. They had head-on completely inelastic collision. After collision they stick to each other and move together. What is magnitude of their combine velocity?

Name: damping
Example question: A damping system has damping factor 0.8 along with spring constant 2 n m^-1 and mass 8 kg. What is the magnitude of constant c (system damping coefficinet)?

Name: elastic energy
Example question: A mass of 5 kg with spring constant 2 N m^-1 in a ideal spring-mass system is in rest state. A mass is displaced by a force from its equilibrium position and spring-mass system gains elastic energy of 0.375 J. By how much distance from equilibrium position mass has displaced?

Name: electromagnetic force
Example question: A charged particle q enters in a perpendicular direction with velocity 1.7 \times 10^4 m s^-1 to the mutually perpendicular electric field and magnetic field of magnitude 4 N m^-1 and 1.4 T respectively. If electromagnetic force experience by charged particle is approximately 0.048 N. What is the magnitude of charge on the particle?

Name: electrostatic force
Example question: If two electrons (1.6 \times 10^-19 C) are separated from each other in the vacuum at distance of 1 \times 10^-8 m. What is the magnitude of electrostatic force of repulsion between two electrons. (1/4 pi epsilon_0 = 9 \times 10^9 N m^2 C^-2)?

Name: energy-momentum relation
Example question: A proton moving at a speed of v = 0.86c and therefore proton has relativistic momentum p = 1580 MeV/c. Proton has a rest energy 938 MeV. What is the magnitude of the relativistic total energies?

Name: escape velocity
Example question: For the Jupiter, equatorial radius is 7.1492 \times 10^7 m and escape velocity is 0.595 \times 10^5 m s^-1. What is the value of the mass of the Jupiter. (Universal gravitational constant = 6.67430 \times 10^-11 m^3 kg^-1 s^-2)?

Name: force
Example question: A force of 10 N acting on the mass of 5 kg. How much acceleration can produce in the mass?

Name: free fall
Example question: A lead ball is thrown from the top of tower with velocity 2 m s^-1. What is its magnitude of velocity after 4 s? The value of acceleration due to gravity is 9.8 m s^-2. Neglect the air resistance.

Name: frequency
Example question: For a tuning fork in Clang mode of vibration, the time period is 0.0004 s. What is the frequency of a tuning fork?

Name: friction
Example question: A force of 300 N is needed to move a 850 N crate across a level surface with constant velocity. What is the value of coefficient of kinetic friction?

Name: gravitational acceleration
Example question: For the Mercury, mass is 3.3011 \times 10^23 kg and equatorial radius is 2439.7 \times 10^3 m. What is the value of acceleration due to gravity on the surface of mercury? (Universal gravitational constant = 6.67430 \times 10^-11 m^3 kg^-1 s^-2)?

Name: gravity
Example question: Two masses 3 kg and 5 kg are separated from each other at distance of 20 m. What is the magnitude of gravitational force of attraction? (Universal gravitational constant = 6.67430 \times 10^-11 m^3 kg^-1 s^-2).

Name: gravitational potential
Example question: The planet mercury revolves around the sun in an elliptical orbit. At its perihelion position, it is located at distnace of 4.6 \times 10^3 m. The mass of planet mercury is 3.285 × 10^23 kg and the sun is 1.989 × 10^30 kg. What is the magnitude of gravitational potential due to sun on mercury at perihelion position? (Universal gravitational constant = 6.67430 \times 10^-11 m^3 kg^-1 s^-2).

Name: Hooke's law
Example question: A spring scale in the shop stretches 3.2 cm from its equilibrium position, when 19.2 N of raw material is weighted. What is the value of spring constant?

Name: jerk
Example question: A mass experiences a change of acceleration of 8 m s^-2 in the arbitrary time interval of 3.2 s. What is the magnitude of jerk produce in the mass?

Name: kinetic energy
Example question: A bullet fired from gun has mass 0.004 kg and constant velocity of 120 m s^-1. What is the kinetic energy of the bullet?

Name: Lagrangian operator
Example question: An ideal spring-mass system is in the state of motion. At certain instant kinetic energy and potential energy of the system is 15 J and 5.6 J respectively. What is the magnitude of Langrangian operator?

Name: Lorentz factor
Example question: An proton is moving at speed of v = 0.86c. What is the value of Lorentz factor for proton?

Name: Lorentz force
Example question: In a velocity selector of blood flowmeter ions moving to the right at 7 \times 10^3 m s^-1. The electric field is 400 V m^-1 into the page. What is the magnitude of the magnetic field?

Name: mass–energy equivalence
Example question: The mass of an electron is 9.1 \times 10^-31 kg. How much is the rest energy of an electron in electron volts?

Name: moment of inertia
Example question: A flywheel is solid, uniform disk of mass 3 kg and radius 10 \times 10^-2 m. What is moment of inertia of the flywheel?

Name: momentum
Example question: During takeoff a rocket has mass (including fuel) 2 \times 10^6 kg and its velocity is 140 m s^-1. What is the momentum of a rocket?

Name: Newton's second law of motion for constant mass
Example question: The mass of the block is 20 kg. If mass is pulled in vertically upwards direction with force 400 N. What is the acceleration of the block? ( Assume no other forces are present, e.g. gravitation)

Name: Newton's third law of motion
Example question: A 200 kg polar bear is standing still near frozen lake in Svalbard, Norway. The acceleration due to gravity at that place is approximately 9.8 m \times s^-2. What is the magnitude of the force with which the polar bear pulls on the Earth?

Name: power
Example question: A man runs up the stairs from ground level to the top of building. He spends 4.2 \times 10^5 J energy to reach the top in 600 s. How much muscular power utilises by man?

Name: radial velocity
Example question: The radius of the centrifuge is 15 \times 10^-2 m and it spins at 270 pi rad s^-1. What is radial velocity of an object moving at the outer edge?

Name: rest energy
Example question: The mass of an electron is 9.109 \times 10^-31 kg. Speed of light is 2.998 \times 10^8 m s^-1. What is magnitude of rest energy associated with the electron?

Name: rest mass
Example question: The rest energy associated with the neutron is 1.5054277 \times 10^-10 J. Speed of light is 2.998 \times 10^8 m s^-1. What is magnitude of rest mass of neutron?

Name: Rossby number
Example question: For the Earth speed at equator, characteristic length, earth's angular frequency and latitude is 10 ms^-1, 6 \times 10^6 m, 7.292 \times 10^-5 rad s^-1 and 45 degrees. What is the value of Rossby number for the Earth?

Name: speed
Example question: A car drives with a speed of 3 m/s. How much distance can it cover in 1 s?

Name: speed of light
Example question: In an electromagnetic spectrum a hard gamma rays has wavelength 1 \times 10^-18 m and frequency 3 \times 10^26 s^-1. What is the speed of light?

Name: sphere
Example question: A sphere has centre at origin. The cartesian co-ordinates of arbitrary point on it surface are (1,2,3). What is the radius of the sphere?

Name: Spherical pendulum
Example question: The amplitude, wavenumber, angular velocity and phase for spherical pendulum is 0.5 m, pi/3 rad m^-1, 2*pi/3 rad s^-1 and pi/2 respectively. What is linear strain in the spherical pendulum at the instant of when location is 2 m and time is 5 s?

Name: Stokes' law
Example question: During experiment light weight pollen grains dropped inside a clear glass cylinder and observed their motion with a microscope. A radius of 15 \times 10^-6 m pollen grain was observed to fall at a rate of 4.7 \times 10^-2 m s^-1. A dynamic viscosity of air inside glass cylinder is 1.849 \times 10^-5 kg m^-1 s^-1. What is magnitudeof frictional force exerting on pollen grains?

Name: stress
Example question: A cross-section area of the bone in the femur of 784 N person is 5.1 \times 10^-4 m^-2. What is the net stress on the femur?

Name: tangential acceleration
Example question: A tip of sprocket-wheel of racing changes the magnitude of tangential velocity from rest to 30 m s^-1 in 1.2 s. What is magnitude of the tangential acceleration of a tip of sprocket-wheel?

Name: tangential velocity
Example question: The tip of a large wind turbine blade is at distance of 40 m from centre of axis of rotation. The magnitude of angular velocity of the blade is 2 rad s^-1. What is the magnitude of tangential velocity?

Name: torque
Example question: To open a giant door of bank vault needs minimum torque of 35 N m when a tangential force F is applied at a distance 1.3 m from the axis of rotation. What is magnitude of force F?

Name: uniform motion
Example question: A yacht makes a short rectilinear trips between two nearby islands with constant velocity of magnitude 14.4 m s^-1 in 372 s. What is the displacement of a yacht in one way trip?

Name: velocity
Example question: An athelete sprints in a straight line for 100 m in 9.2 s. What is his velocity?

Name: wavenumber
Example question: A household microwave oven operates at the wavelength of 12.24 * 10^-2 m. What is the value of corresponding wavenumber?

Name: work
Example question: A dog tugs a sled 5 m on snowy track at a constant speed with  the force of 300 N. How much work does the dog do?
